No comment test exists. Done.

## Report

Fixed BUG G in `C:\repos\dflow\designflow-backend\controllers\comment.controller.js`. All four handlers now have try/catch and return a clean 500 on service errors instead of leaving the async handler rejected (which surfaced as 503/timeouts).

### Diff (before → after)

All four handlers were bare `const x = await CommentService.xxx(...); res.json(x)`. Now:

```js
const getComment = async (req, res) => {
    try {
        const result = await CommentService.getComments(req.params.id);
        res.json(result);
    } catch (err) {
        res.status(500).json({ error: 'SYS-C01', message: err.message });
    }
}

const addComment = async (req, res) => {
    let data;
    try {
        data = await CommentService.addComment(req.body);
        res.json(data);
    } catch (err) {
        res.status(500).json({ error: 'SYS-C02', message: err.message });
        return;
    }
    // ... existing @mention block unchanged below (still fire-and-forget, own try/catch) ...
}
```

`updateComment` → `SYS-C03`, `deleteComment` → `SYS-C04`, same pattern.

### addComment specifics (the critical case)
- The DB write (`CommentService.addComment`) and `res.json(data)` are wrapped; on failure it sends `500` and `return`s before reaching the mention logic.
- The `@mention` notification block stays exactly as it was — after the successful response, still fire-and-forget inside its own `try/catch` that only `console.error`s. It cannot break or delay the response.

### Sibling pattern matched
`controllers/notification.controller.js` — the closest sibling (same service pair, same `getUserInfo` helper, same mention subsystem). It uses `try/catch` with `res.status(500).json({ error: 'SYS-Nxx', message: err.message })`. I matched that shape, continuing the code series with `SYS-C01`–`SYS-C04` (C for comment).

### Verification
- `node -c controllers/comment.controller.js` → SYNTAX_OK.
- No comment controller/service test exists (`tests/unit/` has none matching `comment`), so `npx jest comment` would find nothing to run. The broader suite needs DB/env and can't run meaningfully here.

### Risk
Low. Behavior on the success path is unchanged; only the previously-unhandled error path changed (from a hung/rejected request to a clean 500). One minor visible change: error responses now return JSON `{ error, message }` where before clients got a generic gateway timeout/503 — this is the intended fix and matches repo convention. No commit/push performed; change is in the working tree only.
